parameters: Okay, parts of the shelves should secretly warp players to a duplicate maze where they are chased by one of the creatures.
The chances of it going up should be involved with the collected library cards.
There's a picture book left out on display on top of the shelf.
The book is called "Grisly Bed-Time Tales for Ghoulish Children". Should I take a look?
I can't get the first few pages open without worrying about ripping it.
At least I can get to the second story.
"'Oh, my dear Conrad!' said Mama on one lovely day."
"'Today I need to go out and leave you home all by yourself.'"
"'You need to listen to your Mama when I say this, Conrad. Don't go about sucking your thumb while I am away.'"

"'The great and tall tailor will come to little boys who suck their thumbs before they even realize. Once he arrives, he takes his great sharp scissors and cuts their thumbs clean off where they will never grow back.'"
"As soon as Mama turned her back while leaving through the door, dear Conrad had already placed his thumb in his mouth! Oh dear! Oh dear!"
"Suddenly the door flew open and in he ran!"
"It was the great and tall scissor man!"
"Oh, take a look children! The tailor has come and caught our little Suck-A-Thumb!"
"Snip! Snip! Snip! Both of Conrad's thumbs are now gone!"
"Mama came home to a still and sad Conrad. He showed his thumbless hands to Mama."
"'Aha!' Mama said. 'I knew he would come for you my naughty little Suck-a-Thumb!'"
A pair of \c[4] scissors\c[0] falls out of the book. I take them without thinking.
Now isn't a good time to read.
...It's so sticky that it's partially stuck to the shelf.
If I pick it up, I'll probably rip it.
Definitely not looking at that again.
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]The books here are organized by subject.
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]Try looking at the shelves for other books about birds.
\n<Mitch>When you said this place learns... Is it...?
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]It showed you something painful, didn’t it?
\n<Mitch>...It was like I was back at my desk.
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]I’m sorry I couldn’t come with you. Was it a trap?
\n<Mitch>Hey, you don’t have to cry... Sorry I made you worry like that...
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]...Can you read the book to me, Mitch?
\n<Mitch>“In a small small town, there was a small small tree.”
\n<Mitch>“At the top of the small small tree there was a small small nest. Inside that small small nest was a small small crow.”
\n<Mitch>"This small small crow was named Fred.”
\n<Mitch>"Fred was a lonely lonely bird next to a lonely lonely house."
\n<Mitch>"There was nobody who would stop by and see lonely lonely Fred or the lonely lonely house.”
\n<Mitch>“The only thing Fred had for company was shiny shiny things. He had shiny shiny pebbles, shiny shiny leaves, and shiny shiny paper.”
\n<Mitch>“One day, an old old man moved into the lonely lonely house."
\n<Mitch>“Fred watched the many many people bring many many things into the lonely lonely house.”
\n<Mitch>“Even though many many people brought in many many things, they all ended up leaving old old man alone in the lonely lonely house alongside the many many things.”
\n<Mitch>“Fred began to watch the old old man from his small small nest.”
\n<Mitch>“And cut himself some yummy yummy... bread!”

\n<Mitch>“Fred didn’t realize just how near he had gotten to the lonely lonely house until he had smelled the old old man’s yummy yummy bread. The old old man also realized just how near Fred had gotten.”
\n<Mitch>“So, the old man gave Fred some yummy yummy bread.”
\n<Mitch>“Fred soon found himself coming back to the old old man every day to get more yummy yummy bread. This made the lonely lonely house no longer lonely.”
\n<Mitch>“One day, Fred decided to give the old old man one of his shiny shiny things. This made the old old man give Fred yummy yummy cheese alongside the yummy yummy bread.”
\n<Mitch>“This continued until Fred had run out of shiny shiny things. Fred was afraid that the old old man wouldn’t want to see him anymore if he didn’t have anything to bring him.”
\n<Mitch>“The old old man had made a new new house for Fred! And inside was all of Fred’s shiny shiny things framed and labeled!”
\n<Mitch>“So, Fred and the old old man lived together in the no longer lonely lonely house and enjoyed all the yummy yummy bread and yummy yummy cheese they wanted. The end.”
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]I used to read that to my cousins while babysitting them.
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]And... My mom used to read it to me when I was little.
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]Please. Don’t die here or anywhere near here.
I pick up \c[1]Caroline Pargana's Library Card\c[0].
\n<Caroline>\fi\oc[5]I'll be fine here. Just do your best to get out of here.
The girl is making quick movements with her hands.
Her eyes widen...\! before putting her head down and returning to her seat.
\n<Mitch>...Hold on, can you do that again?
\n<Mitch>“How”... “Long”... Oh! “How long have you been in here”?
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]Wow! You’re the first visitor I’ve seen that knows it!
\n<Mitch>Ha... I took a bunch of classes for it at the Y when I was in middle school.\! Thought it would make me cooler.
\n<Mitch>Turns out, it just made me look more like a nerd.
\n<Mitch>Back then, yeah. Less of a bad thing in college.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]You’re really good at this. I had to learn from the books here.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]Come sit down with me. I can make sure none of the others here bother you for a bit.
\n<Mitch>I mean, you’re nothing like that TV static thing!
\n<Mitch>Haugh... Just looking at him felt like my brain was starting to leak out of my ears...
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]I’m really not upset. It’s just something I’ve accepted.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]Most visitors scream when they see me.
\n<Mitch>Wait. By visitors, do you mean the people who just come to the library?
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]This library. Not the one from the normal world.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]Most arrive by falling asleep in the normal library.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]They’ll find themselves dreaming in this place. Either they’ll wake up on their own or someone will kill them to force them to wake up.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]If you’d like, I can wake you up now. I can make it painless.
\n<Mitch>N-no! I didn’t fall asleep! I just walked in here to get out of the snowstorm!
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]You may have just... slipped through then. That’s not good.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]Usually, that happens with visitors coming from deeper within. That's not good.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]It means you’re here with your physical body. If you die here, there’s no way of knowing what will happen to you.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]The longer you stay, the more it will learn.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]The more it learns, the more ammunition it has to make you suffer.
\n<Mitch>I would’ve run out after the static thing, but all the outside doors are covered in metal vines.
\n<Mitch>After the deer guy shot him, he left behind a library card. That’s the main lead I’ve been following.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]...I was wondering why she told me to hold on to my card all of a sudden.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]I did, but I used it as a bookmark. Sorry.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]It just looks like a certain someone doesn’t want me to be the one to get it.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]It’s a book called “Fred and the Breadman”. Repeat the title back so I know you clearly understand.
\n<Girl>\fi\oc[5]It’s about a crow. You should find it by the books about birds.
\n<Mitch>Oh! Before I go, what’s your name?
\n<Mitch>Thanks for your help. I’m glad to find someone I can trust here.
\n<Mitch>I’ll be right back with that book.
